European Energy Trading Analytics Dashboard (DAX Version)
Project Overview

This project presents an interactive Energy Trading Analytics Dashboard developed using Microsoft Power BI and Advanced DAX, focusing on the analysis of European energy markets during the period 2022–2025.

The dashboard was designed to simulate the analytical workflow of an Energy Market Analyst, Energy Trading Analyst, or Risk Analyst, combining market monitoring, quantitative analysis, and financial risk assessment techniques.

The project investigates the relationships and risk dynamics between major European energy commodities, including:

Brent Crude Oil
Dutch TTF Natural Gas
European Carbon Allowances (EUA)
European Electricity Markets
Project Objectives

The primary objectives of this project were:

Analyze the behavior of European energy markets during the 2022 energy crisis.
Investigate cross-market correlations.
Calculate financial returns and risk metrics using DAX.
Build an interactive business intelligence dashboard for energy trading analysis.
Demonstrate advanced Power BI and DAX analytical capabilities.
Tools & Technologies
Business Intelligence
Microsoft Power BI
Analytics Language
DAX (Data Analysis Expressions)
Data Processing
Python (data cleaning and preparation only)
Dataset

The dashboard analyzes daily market data covering the period:

January 2022 – December 2025
Markets Included
Market	Variable
Oil	Brent Crude Prices
Natural Gas	Dutch TTF Gas Prices
Carbon	EU Carbon Allowances (EUA)
Electricity	European Power Market Index
Data Architecture
Data Preparation

Python was used exclusively for:

Data acquisition
Data cleaning
Missing value treatment
Dataset consolidation

The analytical calculations were performed entirely within Power BI using DAX.

Power BI Data Model

The model consists of:

Fact Table
energy_prices_clean

Containing:

Date
Brent_Price
TTF_Price
EUA_Price
Power_Index
Date Dimension

A dedicated date table was created to support advanced time intelligence calculations.

DateTable =
CALENDAR(
    MIN(energy_prices_clean[Date]),
    MAX(energy_prices_clean[Date])
)
